 = Operating Income + (D&A + SBC + Restructuring + Impairment), this differential implies that the aggregate non-cash/non-recurring add-backs grew more slowly than operating income — and more slowly than revenue. This is consistent with (a) a maturing capital base where incremental D&A from new satellite launches is lagging revenue growth, and (b) share-based compensation scaling sub-linearly with the business. In other words, the GAAP profitability picture is improving even faster than the cash-EBITDA picture, reinforcing the operating-leverage conclusion.\n\n4. **Magnitude of margin expansion (~12 pp in both measures)** is unusually large for a segment already at scale ($7.6B → $11.4B revenue), suggesting Connectivity is passing an inflection point where fixed network costs are largely absorbed and incremental subscribers are highly accretive to profit.\n\n### Caveats\n\n- All figures reflect the retrospectively recast consolidated SpaceX entity (including xAI, merged February 2, 2026, and X Holdings, merged into xAI March 28, 2025) for all historical periods presented. The S-1 states that no period reflects standalone SpaceX operations exclusively; however, the Connectivity segment figures are presented on a segment basis and the recast consolidation primarily affects the consolidated/other segments rather than Connectivity\'s Starlink-driven economics.\n- Segment Adjusted EBITDA is a non-GAAP measure; its construction excludes D&A, SBC, restructuring, and impairment, all of which are economically real costs. The faster growth of GAAP operating income relative to this non-GAAP measure is itself a positive signal, but the EBITDA figure should not be treated as a proxy for free cash flow.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nThe Connectivity segment exhibited pronounced positive operating leverage in FY2025: ~50% revenue growth translated into ~120% operating income growth and ~86% Segment Adjusted EBITDA growth, with both margins expanding by roughly 12 percentage points. The fact that GAAP operating income outgrew Segment Adjusted EBITDA further indicates that non-cash charges (notably D&A and SBC) are scaling sub-linearly with revenue, reinforcing that the segment\'s fixed-cost infrastructure is being monetized with increasing efficiency as the Starlink subscriber base scales.\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Segment Reporting and MD&A sections"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
